  "text": "The Rust compiler's trait obligation solver implements a sophisticated system for resolving trait bounds and detecting unsatisfied trait constraints. The system follows a pipeline architecture with clear separation of concerns.\n\n## Obligation Forest Foundation\nThe `ObligationForest` (compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs) provides the core data structure for managing trait obligations. It maintains a forest of obligation trees where each node represents a pending obligation. The forest supports three processing results: Unchanged (ambiguous), Changed with sub-obligations, and Error. The state machine includes states: Pending -> Success -> Waiting -> Done, or Error. This enables efficient batch processing while tracking obligation dependencies.\n\n## Fulfillment and Obligation Registration\nThe `FulfillmentContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs) wraps the ObligationForest for the old trait solver. When obligations are registered via `ObligationCtxt::register_obligation` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/engine.rs), they become `PendingPredicateObligation` nodes containing the predicate, parameter environment, and recursion depth. The context implements `ObligationProcessor` to handle obligation processing callbacks.\n\n## Trait Selection Pipeline\nThe `SelectionContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs) is the central orchestrator for trait resolution. The selection process follows a well-defined pipeline:\n\n1. **Candidate Assembly**: The `assemble_candidates` method (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs) gathers all possible trait implementations from:\n   - Trait aliases\n   - User-defined implementations\n   - Caller bounds and where-clauses\n   - Builtin implementations (Copy, Clone, Sized, etc.)\n   - Auto-traits\n   - Projection candidates (associated types)\n\n2. **Matching**: The `MatchAgainstFreshVars` type relation (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/_match.rs) tests whether candidate trait references match the obligation. It performs type unification on freshened types to determine if an impl could satisfy the obligation.\n\n3. **Confirmation**: The `confirm_candidate` method (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs) unifies the trait reference with the obligation and produces an `ImplSource` that represents the selected implementation. For user-defined impls, it recursively generates sub-obligations for where-clause bounds.\n\n## Specialization and Impl Matching\nThe specialization system (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/specialize/mod.rs) enforces impl consistency rules. The `OverlapError` structure handles cases where multiple impls could apply. The specialization graph (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/specialize/specialization_graph.rs) organizes impls by their specificity, ensuring that more specific implementations take precedence.\n\n## Associated Type Projection\nThe projection system (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/project.rs) resolves associated types during trait selection. It defines `ProjectionObligation` types and `ProjectionCandidate` sources including parameter environment bounds, trait definitions, object types, and selections. This system integrates with the main trait solver to handle complex generic types with associated type constraints.\n\n## Error Reporting\nWhen obligations cannot be satisfied, the error reporting system provides detailed diagnostics:\n\n- `report_selection_error` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/fulfillment_errors.rs) generates the primary error message, handling multiple error categories including Unimplemented, Unsupported, and TraitNotObjectSafe\n- The error reporting context (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/mod.rs) manages candidate similarity analysis and provides contextual information\n- The suggestions module (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/suggestions.rs) offers actionable fixes\n\n## Type System Integration\nThe trait system integrates with the broader type system through several key types:\n\n- `ObligationCause` (compiler/rustc_middle/src/traits/mod.rs) provides attribution for why obligations exist, including the source span and obligation cause code\n- `FulfillmentError` tracks failed obligations with their error codes and root cause information\n- `Obligation<T>` (compiler/rustc_infer/src/traits/mod.rs) is the generic container for any goal to prove, including recursion depth tracking for termination\n\nThe unified interface allows the same machinery to handle trait predicates, projection predicates, and well-formedness constraints. When obligations become cyclic (detected during forest processing), they are reported as cycle errors with the full backtrace for user understanding."
}

